bihan, Brittany, France","Malestroit, Morbihan, Bretagne, France":"Malestroit, Morbihan, Brittany, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Payen","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French: from the Old French personal name <i>Pagen</i>, <i>Paien</i>, from Latin <i>Paganus</i>, from <i>paganus</i> ‘country-dweller’, a derivative of <i>pagus</i> ‘of or relating to the countryside’, possibly given to a child not yet baptized (because of its later sense of ‘pagan, heathen’). Alternatively, a nickname for a country-born person. This surname is also found in the West Indies (mainly Haiti) and Mauritius.","English: variant of   Payne  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Payan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Ramon, Carlos, Jesus, Leticia, Luis, Ana, Cruz, Juana, Roberto, Rodolfo.","Spanish (<b>Payán</b>): perhaps from Mozarab <i>päiên</i> ‘cave, ravine’, from Hispanic Latin <i>pedia</i>, derived from <i>pedem</i> ‘foot’. In Spain, this surname is found mainly in Andalusia.","French: Occitan variant of   Payen  ."]},{"name":"Pesnell","meanings":["Probably an altered form of French (Normandy) <b>Pesnel</b>: from a vernacular pet form of the old personal name   Payen  , or a topographic name for someone who lived by a fence or palissade, from a shortened form of <i>paissenel</i>, <i>pessenel</i>, a diminutive of <i>paisson</i>, <i>pesson</i> ‘post, stake’. This surname was brought to North America from England."]},{"name":"Pean","meanings":["‘breath, life-force’."]},{"name":"Payne","meanings":["Elaborated spelling of   Jane  , a form popularized no doubt by the American actress  Jayne Mansfield  (  Vera Jayne Palmer ,  1933–67 ) and British ice-dancer  Jayne Torvill  (  b. 1957 )."]}]},{"name":"Il","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["probably a contracted form of  Jep , vernacular form of   Jacob   ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Payen Il de MALESTROIT was born about 1180, his father, Judicael de Malestroit II, was 46 and his mother, Pétronille de Largoet Elven, was 21. He married Constance De Léon in 1205, in Malestroit, Morbihan, Brittany, France. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1229, in Saint-Gildas-de-Rhuys, Morbihan, Brittany, France, at the age of 50."},"et":{"ABT 1180–1229":"umbes 1180–1229","1180–1229":"1180–1229","1185–1237":"1185–1237","1204–1281":"1204–1281","1205–1238":"1205–1238","1135–Male":"1135–Surnud","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","1205":"1205","1238":"1238","1204":"1204","1237":"1237","1135":"1135","1185":"1185","ABT 1180":"umbes 1180","1160":"1160","1281":"1281","1229":"1229","1180":"1180","Saint-Gildas-de-Rhuys,56730,Morbihan,Bretagne,FRANCE,Abbaye de Saint Gildas":"Saint-Gildas-de-Rhuys, Morbihan, Bretagne, Prantsusmaa","Malestroit, Vannes, Morbihan, Bretagne, France":"Malestroit, Morbihan, Bretagne, Prantsusmaa","Malestroit, Morbihan, Bretagne, France":"Malestroit, Morbihan, Bretagne, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"ABT 1180–1229":"noin 1180–1229","1180–1229":"1180–1229","1185–1237":"1185–1237","1204–1281":"1204–1281","1205–1238":"1205–1238","1135–Male":"1135–Kuollut","1160–Female":"1160–Kuollut","1205":"1205","1238":"1238","1204":"1204","1237":"12